2–1416":"1372–1416","1395–1450":"1395–1450","1402–1435":"1402–1435","–1473":"–1473","1328–Male":"1328–Afdød","1328–Female":"1328–Afdød","1414":"1414","1402":"1402","1435":"1435","1379":"1379","1473":"1473","1395":"1395","1450":"1450","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","1416":"1416","Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"nl":{"1379–1414":"1379–1414","1372–1416":"1372–1416","1395–1450":"1395–1450","1402–1435":"1402–1435","–1473":"–1473","1328–Male":"1328–Overleden","1328–Female":"1328–Overleden","1414":"1414","1402":"1402","1435":"1435","1379":"1379","1473":"1473","1395":"1395","1450":"1450","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","1416":"1416","Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"en":{"1379–1414":"1379–1414","1372–1416":"1372–1416","1395–1450":"1395–1450","1402–1435":"1402–1435","–1473":"–1473","1328–Male":"1328–Deceased","1328–Female":"1328–Deceased","1414":"1414","1402":"1402","1435":"1435","1379":"1379","1473":"1473","1395":"1395","1450":"1450","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","1416":"1416","Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Warren","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English (Old French) personal name <i>Warin</i>, <i>Werin</i>, a borrowing of ancient Germanic <i>Warino</i>, a short form of various compound names based on the element <i>warin</i> ‘protection, shelter’ or ‘guard’. Compare   Waring  .","English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from La Varrenne in Seine-Maritime, France, named with a Gaulish element probably descriptive of alluvial land or sandy soil. This was the name of a major Norman family after the Conquest. In Ireland, this name has been Gaelicized as <b>Bharain</b>.","Irish: adopted as an English form of Gaelic <b>Ó Murnáin</b> (see   Murnane  ,   Warner  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Warrens","meanings":["English: variant of   Warren   with genitival or excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Warrener","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): occupational name from Old French <i>warrennier</i> ‘warrener’, an officer employed to watch over game in a park or game preserve. Compare   Warren  ."]},{"name":"Murnane","meanings":["Irish (Munster): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Murnáin</b>, a shortened and dissimilated form of <b>Ó Manannáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Manannán</i>’, name borne in Celtic mythology by a sea god associated with the Isle of Man. All three syllables appear in the variant <b>Marrinan</b>. This name has also been Anglicized as   Warren   and   Warner  ."]},{"name":"Waren","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Warren  ."]},{"name":"Warne","meanings":["shortened form of   Warren  .","occasionally a habitational name from Wearne in Somerset. The place takes its name from a lost stream-name based on British <i>verno-</i> ‘alder, swamp’.","English:"]},{"name":"Waring","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): variant of   Warren  , from the Norman personal name <i>Warin</i>, derived from ancient Germanic <i>Warino</i>, a short form of various compound names based on the element <i>warin</i> ‘protection, shelter’ or ‘guard’. The name was popular in France and among the Normans (see   Guerin  )."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":3,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan Warren was born in 1379, in England, her father, Sir Alfred Alured de Sulney, was 51 and her mother, Mrs Alfred Alured De Sulney, was 51. She had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Sir Nicholas de Longford IV. She died in 1414, at the age of 35."},"et":{"1379–1414":"1379–1414","1372–1416":"1372–1416","1395–1450":"1395–1450","1402–1435":"1402–1435","–1473":"–1473","1328–Male":"1328–Surnud","1328–Female":"1328–Surnud","1414":"1414","1402":"1402","1435":"1435","1379":"1379","1473":"1473","1395":"1395","1450":"1450","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","1416":"1416","Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"1379–1414":"1379–1414","1372–1416":"1372–1416","1395–1450":"1395–1450","1402–1435":"1402–1435","–1473":"–1473","1328–Male":"1328–Kuollut","1328–Female":"1328–Kuollut","1414":"1414","1402":"1402","1435":"1435","1379":"1379","1473":"1473","1395":"13